title: For Sale/Trade:  Smith & Wesson 2nd Model Safety Hammerless, 38 S&W,  Lemon Squeezer 1888
postcontent: I have FS/FT a Nickel Plated Smith & Wesson (2nd Model) Safety Hammerless chambered in the .38 S&W Cartridge (not .38 SPC). This firearm was manufactured in 1888 and has been very well maintained with no signs of refinishing, and has been inspected, tested, and fires to ensure it is safe with modern .38 S&W loads. This firearm maintains roughly 95% of its finish, with some minor wear giving it a nice overall patina. Everything on this fine weapon functions as it was originally designed, to include the ejector and safety systems. This firearm has a 3 & 3/16th inch barrel that has zero pitting or damage to the rifling. This pistol has the original hard rubber grips which have a small break on one side: this is a common issue among these pistols, and replacement grips severely diminish the value. The 2nd Model of Safety Hammerless had several QC improvements over its short lived predecessor, but still had less than ten thousand units produced overall. This is a wonderful piece of history that is ready to endure another 130 years with your family.I am asking $450 OBO for this revolver, which includes roughly $100 dollars worth of ammunition thrown in as a bonus to the buyer. I am not willing to sell the ammunition separately. I am available to meet in most areas of Northern Kentucky with notice. Pistol has been kept in a climate controlled safe, and comes with a Soft Case. Call or text 859 462 9602, more pictures available upon request.Buyer must have a valid Kentucky Driver's license at the minimum, but a CCDW is preferred. postcontent: Vintage 1905 winchester .32WSL (Winchester self loading) The Winchester Model 1905 (also known as the Model 05), is a blowback-operated, semi-automatic rifle produced by the Winchester Repeating Arms Company beginning in 1905 and discontinued in 1920.The 1905 model was the first Winchester semi-auto that used a centerfire cartridge, and the first Winchester to use a detachable box magazine.  Truly an heirloom rifle.The basic design for the Winchester Model 1905 is covered by U.S. Patent 681,481 issued August 27, 1901 and assigned to Winchester by Thomas Crossley Johnson, a key firearms designer for Winchester.
